# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bbc-alba
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] In TV streaming, high-definition television (HDTV) and video display technology, **1080i** is a video display format with 1080 lines of vertical resolution and interlaced scanning method.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This format was once a standard in HDTV.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] It was particularly used for broadcast television because it can deliver high-resolution images without needing excessive bandwidth.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This format is used in the SMPTE 292M standard.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The number "1080" in 1080i refers to the number of horizontal lines that make up the vertical resolution of the display.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Each of these lines contributes to the overall detail and clarity of the image.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This is a technique where the image is not displayed all at once.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Instead, the frame is split into two fields.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] One field contains the odd-numbered lines, and the other field contains the even-numbered lines.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] These fields are displayed in rapid succession, giving the appearance of a full image to the human eye.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The interlacing technique was developed to improve the motion portrayal of images without doubling the required bandwidth.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This is particularly useful in broadcasting, where bandwidth efficiency is crucial.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The frame rate is typically 50 or 60 fields per second, depending on the region.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This effectively means 25 or 30 frames per second when the fields are combined.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] A key difference between 1080i and 1080p is how the lines of resolution are displayed.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Both offer 1920x1080 pixels, but the display method is different.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] In 1080p, the "p" stands for progressive scan.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Each frame is drawn line by line, from top to bottom, creating a complete image in a single pass.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This results in a sharper and more stable picture, especially in fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] On the other hand, 1080i uses an interlaced method.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The two fields that make up a frame are captured at slightly different times, leading to a misalignment in fast-moving parts of the image.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This can cause artifacts like "combing," where fast-moving objects appear to have a serrated edge.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] However, 1080i has been preferred in broadcast television due to its lower bandwidth requirements, making it more efficient for over-the-air or cable transmission.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The origins of 1080i can be traced from Multiple sub-Nyquist sampling encoding, a Japanese analog high-definition television system.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] 1080i emerged as a leading standard for HDTV broadcasts.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The ATSC (Advanced Television Systems Committee) standards and the DVB (Digital Video Broadcasting) standards allowed for the transmission of 1080i video signals.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The adoption of 1080i was particularly significant in sports broadcasting.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The higher resolution allowed for more detail and clarity, especially in large stadium shots and fast-paced action.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The format's efficiency in utilizing available bandwidth made it a practical choice for broadcasters.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] However, it required more complex processing on the receiving end to deinterlace the image for display on progressive-scan screens.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Overall, 1080i played a crucial role in the early days of HDTV.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] It bridged the gap between standard-definition broadcasts and the high-definition future that would soon become the norm.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] While its use has diminished with the rise of 1080p and 4K resolutions, 1080i remains an important milestone in the evolution of television technology.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This means that each video frame has 1,920 pixels horizontally and 1,080 pixels vertically.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This results in over two million individual pixels per frame.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This high resolution is why 1080i is called "high-definition".
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] It offers a significant improvement over standard-definition formats, which typically have much lower pixel counts.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The 1920x1080 resolution allows for greater detail and clarity in images.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This makes it ideal for larger screens where higher pixel density is essential to maintain image quality.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The increased resolution is particularly noticeable in fine details such as textures, text, and intricate patterns.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] These can be rendered with much greater accuracy than in lower-resolution formats.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This refers to how each video frame is displayed.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Instead of showing the entire frame at once, the interlacing technique divides each frame into two separate fields.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The first field contains all the odd-numbered lines (1, 3, 5, etc.), and the second field contains all the even-numbered lines (2, 4, 6, etc.).
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] These two fields are displayed one after the other.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The odd lines are shown first, followed by the even lines.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This happens very quickly, around 50 or 60 fields per second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The human eye sees these two fields as a single, continuous image.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The main advantage of interlacing is that it allows for a higher frame rate without needing more bandwidth.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This results in smoother motion, especially for content with moderate to fast movement, like sports broadcasts.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] However, interlacing also has some drawbacks.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Since the two fields are captured at slightly different times, fast-moving objects can appear misaligned between the two fields.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This creates a visual artifact called "combing." This can reduce image quality, especially in scenes with a lot of motion.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Modern display devices often use deinterlacing algorithms to combine the two fields into a single progressive image before displaying it.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The frame rate of 1080i is usually 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] In areas using the PAL or SECAM standards, like Europe and parts of Asia, the frame rate is 50 Hz.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] In regions using NTSC, like North America and Japan, the frame rate is 60 Hz.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The frame rate refers to how often a new field is shown per second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] At 50 Hz, 50 fields are shown each second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This results in 25 full frames per second when the odd and even fields are combined.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] At 60 Hz, 59.94 fields are shown per second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This results in 29.97 full frames per second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Interlacing affects how motion is perceived in 1080i.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Since each field represents a slightly different moment in time, motion can appear smoother compared to lower frame rate progressive scans.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] However, this also means 1080i can struggle with fast-moving scenes.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The interlaced fields might not perfectly align, leading to motion artifacts.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The European Broadcasting Union (EBU) prefers to use the resolution and *frame rate* (not field rate) separated by a slash, as in *1080i/29.97* and *1080i/25*, likewise 480i/29.97 and 576i/25.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] The 1080i video signals can be carried by four main digital television broadcast systems: ATSC, DVB, ISDB and DTMB.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] In both ATSC and DVB systems, the 1080i signal is compressed using codecs like MPEG-2 or H.264 to reduce the bandwidth required for transmission.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] In the United States, 1080i is the preferred format for most broadcasters, with Warner Bros.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Discovery, Paramount Global, and Comcast owned networks broadcasting in the format, along with most smaller broadcasters.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Only Fox- and Disney-owned television networks, along with MLB Network and a few other cable networks, use 720p as the preferred format for their networks; A&E Networks channels converted from 720p to 1080i sometime in 2013 due to acquired networks already transmitting in the 1080i format.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] This also allows local newscasts on these ABC affiliates to be produced in the higher resolution (especially for weather forecasting presentation purposes for map clarity) to match the picture quality of their 1080i competitors.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Motion pictures shot on film to fit a 16:9 widescreen format (1.78:1) are typically intended to be played back at 24 frames per second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] When telecined and played back at the PAL standard 25 frames per second, films run 4.16% faster than the original, and 4.27083% faster than the NTSC film standard 23.976023976 frames per second.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] High-definition television (HDTV) broadcast standards utilize 1080i (interlaced) or 720p (progressive) formats, typically offering 1920x1080 resolution.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] Key, region-specific formats include 1080i25 for PAL (50 fields/second), 1080i30 for NTSC (60 fields/second), and 1080i24 for film, often converted via telecine for 25/30 frames per second, 1080i50/60 broadcasts.
[src:bbc-alba/1080i] PAL speed-up does not occur on footage intended for playback at 25 frames per second.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-championship] The **2015–16 Scottish Championship** (referred to as the **Ladbrokes Championship** for sponsorship reasons) was the 22nd season in the current format of 10 teams in the second tier of Scottish football.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-championship] Rangers won the league title and promotion after a 1–0 win against Dumbarton on 5 April 2016, while Alloa Athletic were relegated after a 0–0 draw against Livingston on 2 April 2016.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-championship] The following teams have changed division since the 2014–15 season.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-championship] Teams play each other four times, twice in the first half of the season (home and away) and twice in the second half of the season (home and away), making a total of 36 games.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-championship] Livingston, the second bottom team, entered into a 4-team playoff with the 2nd-4th placed teams in 2015–16 Scottish League One; Ayr United, Peterhead, and Stranraer.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-championship] The winners of the semi-finals, Ayr United and Stranraer, competed against one another over two legs, with the winner, Ayr, replacing Livingston and being promoted to the 2016–17 Scottish Championship.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The **2015–16 Scottish Junior Cup** was the 130th season of the Scottish Junior Cup, the national knockout tournament for member clubs of the Scottish Junior Football Association.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The competition was sponsored by ETHX Energy and known as **The ETHXenergy Scottish Junior Cup**.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The winner of this competition entered the following season's Scottish Cup at the first round stage.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] A total of 158 clubs entered this year's competition, three fewer than the previous season.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] Dropping out were Ballingry Rovers, who folded, and Harthill Royal, Luncarty, Portgordon Victoria and Whitehills, who were in abeyance.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] North Region sides Glentanar and Islavale did not enter.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] New members Easthouses Lily MW and Gartcairn FA Juniors made their debut in the competition, while Coupar Angus and Fochabers returned to the tournament after a year in abeyance.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] Also qualified automatically were Banks O'Dee and Linlithgow Rose who achieved national club licensing requirements and Girvan who qualify automatically as historic full members of the Scottish Football Association.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The first round draw took place at Hampden Park, Glasgow on 27 August 2015.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The second round draw took place at Mar Hall, Erskine on 6 October 2015.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The third round draw took place at The Sun offices in Glasgow on 3 November 2015.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The fourth round draw took place at the Evening Times offices in Glasgow on 9 December 2015.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] 3 Match played at Kennoway Star Hearts F.C.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The fifth round draw took place in Glasgow City Chambers on 26 January 2016.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The draw for the quarter-finals took place on 25 February 2016.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The draw for the semi-finals took place on 22 March 2016.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The Final of The ETHX Energy Junior Cup was played at Rugby Park, Kilmarnock on Sunday 29 May with a 4.05pm kick off.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-junior-cup] The game was televised live by BBC ALBA.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-league-one] The **2015–16 Scottish League One** (referred to as the **Ladbrokes League One** for sponsorship reasons) was the 22nd season in the current format of 10 teams in the third-tier of Scottish football.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-league-one] Cowdenbeath, the second bottom team, entered into a 4-team playoff with the 2nd-4th placed teams in 2015–16 Scottish League Two; Elgin City, Clyde, and Queen's Park.
[src:bbc-alba/2015-16-scottish-league-one] The winners of the semi-finals, Clyde and Queen's Park, then competed against one another over two legs, with the winner replacing Cowdenbeath and being promoted to the 2016–17 Scottish League One.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] The **2019–20 season of the Frauen-Bundesliga** was the 30th season of Germany's premier women's football league.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] VfL Wolfsburg won their fourth straight and sixth overall title.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic in Germany, on 8 March 2020 the Federal Minister of Health, Jens Spahn recommended cancelling events with more than 1,000 people.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] On 13 March, the DFB announced that a match scheduled for 15 March, was postponed.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] On 16 March, it was announced that the league will be suspended until 19 April.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] After a meeting on 31 March, the suspension was extended until 30 April.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] A decision on the resumption of the competition, similar to the Bundesliga and 2.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] Bundesliga, was taken at an extraordinary meeting of the DFB-Bundestag on 25 May 2020.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] On 20 May, it was announced that the league will be continued on 29 May.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] All matches were played behind closed doors.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] In addition, five substitutions were permitted for the remaining matches, following a proposal from FIFA and approval by IFAB to lessen the impact of fixture congestion.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored; 4) Head-to-head points; 5) Head-to-head goal difference; 6) Head-to-head goals scored; 7) Head-to-head away goals scored; 8) Away goals scored; 9) Play-off.
[src:bbc-alba/2019-20-frauen-bundesliga] Legend: Blue = home team win; Yellow = draw; Red = away team win.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] In August 2004, the London Development Agency (LDA) acquired 3 Mills Studios.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] As parent organisation of the *Creative London* agency, the LDA's role included supporting business and skills, researching industry needs, and promoting London for film-making.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] The site is now one of London's most important film and television studios.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] Ownership transferred to the London Legacy Development Corporation in 2010 which is the organisation responsible for planning, developing, and managing the Olympic Park after the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has over 75,000 sq ft (7,000 m2) of filming space, including 11 filming stages and nine rehearsal rooms.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] Stage 5 at 10,437 sq ft (969.6 m2) has a similar floor size to the Royal Albert Hall.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] There are nine rehearsal rooms on site: Rehearsal Room 6 at 2,507 sq ft (232.9 m2) is the largest and Rehearsal Room 3 at 280.9 sq ft (26.10 m2) is the smallest.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has a large range of ancillary spaces including; production offices, props workshops, five prop stores ranging from 712 to 1,319 sq ft (66.1 to 122.5 m2), make-up rooms, and dressing rooms.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] Many feature films have been made at 3 Mills Studios, including *Legend*, *Topsy-Turvy*, *Sexy Beast*, *Eastern Promises*, *Attack the Block*, *Berberian Sound Studio*, *Ill Manors*, *Powder Room*, *Made in Dagenham*, *Never Let Me Go*, *Farming* and *Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels*.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios' main focus has been on television shows.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios has been home to BBC's *MasterChef* since 2014.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills was home to Channel 4's *Big Brother* for the first and second series along with the first series of *Celebrity Big Brother*.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] Other clients include Matthew Bourne's New Adventures, English National Opera, Raymond Gubbay Limited, Shakespeare's Globe and English National Ballet, as well as advertisers for Versace, Audi, Waitrose, Nissan, Gillette, Samsung, Gucci, Topshop, B&Q and Adidas.
[src:bbc-alba/3-mills-studios] 3 Mills Studios also housed many rehearsals for the opening and closing ceremonies of the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] The 1503 frequency had been previously vacated by 3AK as it moved to occupy 1116 AM The first test broadcast was in 1998.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] 3KND was one of the later entrants into the temporary community broadcasting period in Melbourne as part of the lead up to the granting of four additional community licences for the City.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] It was granted the only AM license available for community radio at that time.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] 3KND was licensed at the same time as JOY 94.9, for the LGBT community; Christian contemporary-formatted Triple 7 (now LightFM); and the student-run SYN FM (now SYN 90.7) At the time it was founded, 3KND was Melbourne's first Indigenous radio station.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] Official broadcasting began in June 2003.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] Internet streaming was introduced in 2006.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] 3KND was one of nine Melbourne community radio stations to launch a digital radio (specifically, DAB+) service during an historic simulcast from Federation Square on 14 April 2011.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] Since 2016, 3KND has published a *Top 100 indigenous songs* list.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] In 2019, those top songs are numbered from 100 down to 1 for the first time, with top honours going to Ruby Hunter's *Proud, Proud Women*, the first song she wrote.
[src:bbc-alba/3knd] 3KND's internet streaming is provided by Internode (ISP).
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] As of 2012, BBC Alba had an average viewership of 637,000 adults over the age of 16 in Scotland each week.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] In 2007, the BBC Trust opened a consultation for a Gaelic digital service in partnership with the Gaelic Media Service.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] On 28 January 2008, the BBC Trust gave the go-ahead for a Gaelic channel.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The channel began broadcasting on satellite at 9:00 pm on 19 September 2008 with a launch video featuring a new rendition of the Runrig song, **Alba**.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The first part of a live *cèilidh* from Skye, presented by Mary Ann Kennedy, was followed by a specially produced comedy-drama entitled **Eilbheas** (Elvis), starring Greg Hemphill as Elvis Presley, at 9:30 pm.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The channel's first independent commission, **Peter Manuel – Deireadh an Uilc?** (*Peter Manuel - The End of Evil?*), a drama-documentary produced by STV Productions, was shown at 10:30 pm before the opening night closed with the second half of the live *cèilidh* from Skye.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The launch night was simulcast on BBC Two Scotland between 9:00 pm and 10:30 pm and a launch event was held at the National Museum of Scotland, which was recorded by the channel's news service **An Là**.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] A study carried out for the channel indicated that 650,000 people watched BBC Alba per week in the first two months of broadcasting, in spite of only being available to around a third of Scots.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] This was approved by the BBC Trust on 27 December 2010 and the service launched on Freeview on 8 June 2011.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The channel also launched on Virgin Media (Scotland only) on 18 May 2011, and was made available nationwide on the Virgin Media and Sky platforms, the former on 6 November 2012.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba is broadcast for up to seven hours a day in the United Kingdom on satellite platforms Sky and Freesat, cable provider Virgin Media and on digital terrestrial provider Freeview in Scotland only.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba simulcasts the BBC's Gaelic-language radio service BBC Radio nan Gàidheal as well during the day after midnight (1am on Saturday night), which in turn simulcasts BBC Radio Scotland overnight.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Programmes are also available to watch on the Internet live through services including the BBC iPlayer and some programmes are available for 30 days (or more) after broadcast on this service and on catch-up services of some other services.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] On 8 September 2022, BBC Alba had to pause programming at around 6:30pm due to the death of Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Normal programming resumed the following day at 7pm.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The channel is financed from the BBC Scotland budget and by MG Alba, which itself is financed by the Scottish Government and the UK government.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] In 2011/12 the BBC spent £8 million on the channel, of which £5 million was used for programming.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] MG Alba spends the majority of its budget (£12.4 million in 2008/09) on the Gaelic Digital Service.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba continuity presentation and channel management is based in Stornoway, while the news services are based in Inverness.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Scotland's headquarters at Pacific Quay in Glasgow is used to transmit the programmes.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The BBC have confirmed that BBC Alba HD will launch online and on various platforms between October 2021 and the end of 2022.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba combines television, radio and on-line programme content.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba broadcasts more Scottish sport than any other channel, with over three hours a week of football, rugby and shinty.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] In addition, the station also broadcasts a live news programme every day, with the weekend news provision beginning in 2018.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Output on the channel consists of news, current affairs, sport, drama, documentary, entertainment, education, religion and children's programming, broadcast on most days between 5 pm and midnight.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Children's programmes are shown for two hours every weekday, between 17:00 and 19:00.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Starting in 2018, a rebranding initiative saw the first hour presented as 'CBeebies Alba' and the second hour as 'CBBC Alba'.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] They are the Scottish Gaelic versions of the CBBC and CBeebies channels.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Most of the adult programming on BBC Alba contains on-screen English subtitles.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] For logistical reasons, live broadcasts (including the news) are not subtitled, although certain events (e.g. the annual Hogmanay broadcast **Bliadhna Mhath Ùr**) have scripted elements that are subtitled, while interviews and ad-libbed lines are not.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Children's programmes are not subtitled.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Controversially, no English dialogue on the channel is subtitled into Scottish Gaelic.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba concentrates on four sports: football, rugby, shinty, and curling.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] During the 2009–10 season, the station broadcast one full Scottish Premier League game every Saturday night.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The game selected was always one not covered by either live Sky Sports or on an on-demand basis by BT Vision and was shown three hours after the end of the match.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The matches only included Gaelic commentary along with English subtitles.The channel reached an agreement with the Scottish Football League to broadcast live football games during the 2008–09 season.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] This began with the final of the Challenge Cup, which was also sponsored by MG Alba.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba then started broadcasting First Division games, beginning with the match between Airdrie United and Clyde on 22 February 2009.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] BBC Alba also struck a deal with the Scottish rugby authorities to show one live Scottish Premiership Division One match every weekend.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] For the 2015–16 season, BBC Alba will show 20 live matches (excluding Rangers) from either the 2015-16 Scottish Championship (including the play-off final), League 1 or League 2, as well as four matches from the Scottish Challenge Cup.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The station also altered their coverage of Scottish Premiership highlights, showing one-hour highlights of two non-televised matches on a Saturday and Sunday night at 22:00.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Other football coverage includes all Scotland U21s and Women's matches, as well as the final of the 2015-16 Scottish Junior Cup.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] In 2010 BBC Alba bought the rights for Celtic League rugby jointly with public service broadcasters from the Republic of Ireland, Northern Ireland and Wales.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] In May 2020, BBC Alba broadcast the last five matches of Women's Bundesliga.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] A number of independent companies have been commissioned to produce content for the channel, or have productions currently airing.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The Gaelic community, including writers Aonghas MacNeacail, Angus Peter Campbell, Lisa Storey and musician Allan MacDonald, have criticised the non-availability of Gaelic subtitles, and the emphasis on English-language interviews and reportage in the channel's content for adults.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Writers and authors were reported by the BBC Gaelic news service as setting up a campaign, GAIDHLIG.TV, to increase Gaelic content on BBC Alba.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The decision to introduce 'red button facilities' to allow viewers to switch to English-language sports commentary, first announced in August 2014 for rugby and the Guinness Pro12 series, was heavily criticised by the Gaelic community.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The criticism resulted in MG Alba announcing publicly in the West Highland Free Press that the 'red button option' for English-language commentary would not expand to other sports or areas of the channel.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] Between its launch in September 2008 and the beginning of 2010, the BBC Alba channel lost a third of its viewers, but its number of viewers remains five times larger than the size of the Gaelic speech community in Scotland (just over 58,000).
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The historian Michael Fry has argued that many of its viewers only watch it for the football coverage, because "you don't need Gaelic to watch football", and that in this way the channel is "cheating".
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The model is, however, both common and intentional as it is on comparable channels such as the Irish language channel TG4, the Basque broadcaster EITB or the Welsh channel S4C.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] In Europe, these channels' main mission is not commercial, but the promotion of the original languages.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] On 19 May 2011, it was reported that the BBC has backed down on the plans, after the BBC had "managed to reengineer facilities" to allow BBC Radio 1Xtra, 5 Live and 6 Music to continue to broadcast on a 24-hour basis.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] The three stations were chosen because they have the highest evening audience ratings on digital television of the seven BBC radio stations unavailable on FM radio.
[src:bbc-alba/bbc-alba] On 2 December 2013, it was confirmed that more radio stations were made available 24 hours in Scotland, but with some trade-offs.
